{"add":{"doc":{"id":"b14318b22e37a31674a2313a25995753acd416b6da1291566a05048a8e336d06","url":"https://upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/7/75/Sparta_ruins.PNG/220px-Sparta_ruins.PNG","previous":[],"after":["Thucydides believed that the Peloponnesian War represented an event of unmatched magnitude.[27] As such, he began to write the History at the onset of the war in 431.[28][29] His intention was to write an account of the events of the late fifth century which would serve as \"a possession for all time\".[30] The history breaks off near the end of the 21st year of the war and does not elaborate on the final conflicts of the war. This facet of the work suggests that Thucydides died whilst writing his history and more so, that his death was unexpected."]}}}